<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-05-23T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-05-23T23:00:00-05:00" n="319" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d319">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">365D.1115/13: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Consul at Aden</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Timberlake</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-05-24T00:00:00-04:00">May 24,
                                        1941—midnight</date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>15. Your telegram May 8. It is extremely unlikely that American
                                vessels can be made available for the movement of Italian civilians
                                from Berbera to South Africa. The only American vessels operating in
                                the area referred to are cargo vessels which, of course, could not
                                handle any great number of passengers. Also, the vessels which might
                                come into position for this purpose are urgently needed for the
                                transportation to the United States of materials required for the
                                national defense.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>